Originally, and for the first few decades, JPL was 
just strictly, let's face it, working for the Army

29:14.228 --> 29:23.356
as a contractor developing weapons. When you 
first came here, was that still a situation? Yes.

29:29.602 --> 29:31.044
OK. When did JPL get handed over to the Army? Well, 
we did, of course, work with the Army in putting up

29:38.791 --> 29:47.204
the initial explorers. And then when we were 
talking with the Army and with the defense people

29:48.105 --> 30:03.969
about doing additional space-type missions that 
were more researched than anything else before

29:48.105 --> 30:03.969
NASA came into existence. But NASA then, of 
course, was founded. Immediately, they were told

30:09.335 --> 30:23.867
that they could take over existing laboratories 
if the laboratories were willing to be taken over

30:09.335 --> 30:23.867
to work with them on the space program that had been 
proposed. So they said, well, since we had worked

30:24.505 --> 30:32.474
on the explorers, where the obvious place to turn 
to, they'd like to have JPL. And people at JPL were

30:32.514 --> 30:34.957
very enthused about this. Most of the people here 
felt they'd much rather work on studies of the

30:35.057 --> 30:51.216
solar system than they would work on military 
field artillery, long-range field rockets, and

30:35.057 --> 30:51.216
that kind of thing, especially since that 
knowledge was applicable to the new space program

30:35.057 --> 30:51.216
as well. So that by... The end of 58, everybody here 
was very enthused about being a part of NASA. I

30:58.714 --> 31:04.729
think it was in 58 that NASA took us over then with 
great enthusiasm on everybody's part here. Not

31:04.769 --> 31:13.429
that we disliked the Army people we worked for, and 
I mean, in some ways, working for the Army was a

31:04.769 --> 31:13.429
rather pleasant experience in that we had a real 
skunk works approach to things in those days and

31:14.185 --> 31:39.130
the army would sort of come in with a bucket of money 
and suggest that we do some work in an area and the

31:14.185 --> 31:39.130
people here would kind of decide how the money 
should be spent and if there were a lot of money in

31:14.185 --> 31:39.130
the bucket at the end of the year no one was 
concerned about it that there might be any less the

31:14.185 --> 31:39.130
next year because we hadn't spent at all I mean they 
spent what they had to spend to get the job done and

31:39.380 --> 31:46.876
And if the bucket ran dry for some reason, why, 
they'd simply go back to the Army and say, hey, you

31:39.380 --> 31:46.876
know, can you fill up the bucket partway again? And 
usually the bucket would get filled up. And nobody

31:49.421 --> 31:58.300
was concerned in those days about which charge 
number to charge this hour's work to, or it was just

31:59.140 --> 32:07.088
There were broad tasks being assigned at JPL, and 
the people here decided how best to carry them out,

31:59.140 --> 32:07.088
and the money always seemed available. So in that 
sense, the working relationship was great. It was

32:11.232 --> 32:12.033
ideal. But, of course, the work being done was work 
on missiles like the Sergeant, for example. So the

32:20.101 --> 32:24.625
whole idea of converting our expertise over to 
Learning more about the solar system was just, I

32:24.942 --> 32:31.965
don't know, I think everybody reacted with great 
enthusiasm, with a few exceptions.

